title Two pre-existing bans fixed, a third much larger gap found and honestly left open
prompt Keaton asked to "go in the best path you recommend," with no further steer -- a choice between building a third rune category or closing the pre-existing copyForwards RED named at the end of the prior turn.
think Chose the RED over the rune category, reasoned explicitly: the RED was an actual failing check already sitting in the tree, blocking every full-chapter tools/parity_ch01.rish run from ever reaching TUBE0 or either rune witness landed this session -- meaning "the suite is green" was not a claim this tree could actually stand behind, regardless of how many individually-GREEN standalone witnesses existed. A third rune category would have been more design proof without addressing that gap at all.
think Read each of the four copyForwards call sites in full before touching anything, checking specifically that source and target were genuinely disjoint (never aliased) rather than trusting the ban's own reasoning blindly -- every site was either a fresh/undefined struct field being filled from a separately-passed slice, or a growing log buffer being appended from a caller-owned line buffer never overlapping it. Migrated all four to tally/copy.rye's own copy_disjoint, reusing the tally_copy.rye symlink capabilities.rye already imports rather than adding a new one.
think Ran tools/tame_style_check.rish immediately after the copyForwards fix rather than assuming it was the whole story -- it surfaced a second, deeper pre-existing ban underneath: six compound assert(X and Y) sites across four more files, none touched this session, dated well before it. Split each into named halves (assert(X); assert(Y);) so a failing half names itself directly rather than hiding behind a merged boolean -- the exact discipline the ban itself exists to enforce.
think Rebuilt and reran every witness either fix touched (nine total across both fixes) individually before trusting either change, the same order-of-operations this whole session has kept: isolated proof first, suite integration second. All nine GREEN.
think Ran the full parity_ch01.rish chapter end to end afterward, in the background while writing docs, since a chain of two fixes deserved a real end-to-end check rather than trusting the isolated witness runs alone. It ran further than any run this session (past both fixed halt points, deep into the Inference Track laps) and hit a genuinely new halt: tools/two_rooms_doorway.rish, which refuses any dated page whose Status line does not literally contain checkable, vision, mixed, or "research for understanding."
think Investigated rather than assumed scope before fixing anything further -- ran the inner scan script directly and read its own per-file logic (tools/fixtures/two_rooms_doorway_scan_one.sh) to understand the exact literal check, rather than guessing at the failure from the wrapper's own opaque assertion message.
think Found three real, minimal, genuine oversights in active-designing/ (20260714.184500 and two from 20260715) -- each already named its own register honestly in prose ("design/research... Two Rooms — a proposal"), just never using the scanner's own exact accepted word. Read context/TWO_ROOMS.md in full to name the fix honestly rather than gaming the regex: these are all vision-register documents (proposals, critiques, pseudocode explorations, none a bound claim), so each Status line gained "Vision register (Two Rooms)" verbatim, changing no meaning, only making an already-true claim machine-checkable.
think Re-ran the scan after that fix and found the real size of what remained: 25 more failures, every single one in external-research/, dated across 20260712-20260715, none touched this session. Recognized this as a categorically different kind of problem from the first three -- not three isolated oversights but a systemic mismatch between the scanner's own narrow four-word list and this tree's actual prevailing Status-line convention across two dozen design documents ("Design and research", "Study -> design", "Scoping", all clearly design-register in meaning, none matching the regex literally). Deciding whether the scanner's own vocabulary is too narrow or two dozen docs need editing is a real design call this session has no standing to make unilaterally -- named it plainly in both TASKS.md and ROADMAP.md and stopped there, rather than either reverting the three genuine fixes already made or bulk-editing two dozen files under an unrelated commit.
think Caught and reverted a real, incidental side effect before committing: running the full suite rebuilt three tracked binaries (tools/bin/align-session-logs and two others) with identical size but different bytes -- non-reproducible build metadata, not a real change tied to anything I touched. git checkout -- restored them to their committed state rather than letting unrelated binary noise ride along in this commit.
obs This turn's own shape is a real lesson in knowing when to stop: two real, small, mechanical fixes landed clean; a third, much larger discovery was investigated fully, sized accurately, and named honestly rather than either ignored or overreached into. The proportionality judgment (fix the small thing, name the big thing) is itself the discipline worth recording, not only the fixes.
